context: East Tucson is relatively new compared to other parts of the city, developed <a6_0>between the 1950s and the 1970s<a6_0/>,[citation needed] with developments such as <a0_0>Desert Palms Park<a0_0/>. It is generally classified as the area of the city east of <a7_0>Swan Road<a7_0/>, with above-average real estate values relative to the rest of the city. The area includes urban and suburban development near the Rincon Mountains. <a5_0>East<a5_0/> Tucson includes <a1_0>Saguaro National Park East<a1_0/>. Tucson's "Restaurant Row" is also located on the east side, along with a significant corporate and financial presence. Restaurant Row is sandwiched by three of Tucson's storied Neighborhoods: <a2_0>Harold Bell Wright Estates<a2_0/>, named after the famous author's ranch which occupied some of that area prior to the depression; the Tucson Country Club (the third to bear the name Tucson Country Club), and the Dorado Country Club. Tucson's largest office building is <a8_0>5151 East Broadway<a8_0/> in east Tucson, completed in <a3_0>1975<a3_0/>. The first phases of Williams Centre, a mixed-use, master-planned development on Broadway near Craycroft Road, were opened in 1987. <a4_0>Park Place<a4_0/>, a recently renovated shopping center, is also located <a9_0>along Broadway (west of Wilmot Road)<a9_0/>.
